<H2>fio: A disk IO performance analysis tool</H2></tr>

<tr><td><table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=0 cellspacing=9><tr><td width=10% valign=center align=center><font size=2 color=#333333><a href=/voteup/?inode=11901><img src=up.gif border=0 alt="Up"></a><br>vote<br><a href=/votedown/?inode=11901><img src=down.gif border=0 alt="Down"></a></font></td><td width=1 bgcolor=#bbbbbb><br></td>
<td width=90% valign=top></b>
<table width=90% cellspacing=8 border=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td><font size=3>fio is conveniently accessable for Fedora and Debian-based distributions...<br><blockquote>fio was created to allow benchmarking specific disk IO workloads. It can issue its IO requests using one of many synchronous and asynchronous IO APIs, and can also use various APIs which allow many IO requests to be issued with a single API call. You can also tune how large the files fio uses are, at what offsets in those files IO is to happen at, how much delay if any there is between issuing IO requests, and what if any filesystem sync calls are issued between each IO request.</blockquote> <a href="http://www.linux.com/feature/131063">read more...</a></font></table></table><tr><td><font size=2 color=#666666><a href="MailLink/?inode=11901">mail this link</a> | <a href="?inode=11901">permapage</a> | score:9937 | </font><font size=2> -Ray, April 9, 2008</table><table><tr><td height=8></table>
<table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td height=3 bgcolor=#1166bb></tr>
<tr><td>

<H2>Performance tradeoffs of TCP Selective Acknowledgment</H2></tr>

<tr><td><table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=0 cellspacing=9><tr><td width=10% valign=center align=center><font size=2 color=#333333><a href=/voteup/?inode=11899><img src=up.gif border=0 alt="Up"></a><br>vote<br><a href=/votedown/?inode=11899><img src=down.gif border=0 alt="Down"></a></font></td><td width=1 bgcolor=#bbbbbb><br></td>
<td width=90% valign=top></b>
<table width=90% cellspacing=8 border=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td><font size=3>Recently there has been significant discussion of  Linux's TCP SACK implementation, and its weakness within the Linux TCP stack. SACK is an optional feature of TCP necessary for effective use of all available bandwidth of some networks. However, processing this type of acknowledgment can be CPU intensive for the TCP sender, and thus a weakness which can be exploited by a malicious peer.  <a href="http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/linux/library/l-tcp-sack/?ca=dgr-lnxw16LinuxTCPSACK&amp;S_TACT=105AGX59&amp;S_CMP=GR">read more...</a></font></table></table><tr><td><font size=2 color=#666666><a href="?inode=11899">permapage</a> | score:9936 | </font><font size=2> -Ida Momtaheni, April 10, 2008</table><table><tr><td height=8></table>
<table width=100% border=0 cellspacing=0><tr><td height=3 bgcolor=#1166bb></tr>
<tr><td>

