<H2>Stopping cross-site scripting attacks</H2></tr>

<tr><td><table border=0 width=100% cellpadding=0 cellspacing=9><tr><td width=10% valign=center align=center><font size=2 color=#333333><a href=/voteup/?inode=11891><img src=up.gif border=0 alt="Up"></a><br>vote<br><a href=/votedown/?inode=11891><img src=down.gif border=0 alt="Down"></a></font></td><td width=1 bgcolor=#bbbbbb><br></td>
<td width=90% valign=top></b>
<table width=90% cellspacing=8 border=0 cellpadding=0><tr><td><font size=3>Cross-site scripting (XSS) is one of the most common application-level attacks that hackers use to sneak into Web applications. Learn  how hackers launch an attack, what damage it does, how to detect them, and how to prevent your Web site and your visitors from these invasions of privacy. <a href="http://www.ibm.com/developerworks/rational/library/08/0325_segal/index.html?ca=dgr-lnxw16cross-sitescrip&amp;S_TACT=105AGX59&amp;S_CMP=GRsitelnxw16">read more...</a></font></table></table><tr><td><font size=2 color=#666666><a href="?inode=11891">permapage</a> | score:9912 | </font><font size=2> -jmalasko, April 8, 2008</table><table><tr><td height=8></table>
